{{Infobox person | name = John W. Dwinelle<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | image = John W. Dwinelle.jpg<!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = John W. Dwinelle, date unknown | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1816|9|9|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Cazenovia, New York]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1881|1|28|1816|9|9|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Port Costa, California]] | nationality = American | other_names = | occupation = | known_for = }}
'''John Whipple Dwinelle''' (September 9, 1816 – January 28, 1881)<ref name="NYT">{{cite news | title=THE LATE MR. DWINELLE | work=[[New York Times]] | date=12 Feb 1881 | pages=8}}</ref><ref name="HLM">{{cite book|title=Hamilton Literary Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uSsTAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA365|accessdate=20 June 2013|year=1882|publisher=Courier Press|pages=365–66|chapter=Class of 1834}}</ref> was an American lawyer and politician. He served in a number of political posts in California and played important roles in both the legal history of San Francisco and the establishment of the California public university system.
Dwinelle was born in [[Cazenovia, New York]], the son of Congressman [[Justin Dwinell]] and Louise Whipple, a descendant of [[William Whipple]]. He graduated from [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]] in 1834. While studying law, he edited the ''[[New York Daily Gazette]]'', the ''[[Daily Buffalonian]]'', and edited and [[typeset]] the ''[[Rochester Daily Advertiser]]''. Dwinelle was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in October 1837 and began a legal practice in [[Rochester, New York]]. In 1844 he was elected [[city attorney]] of Rochester. The next year he became master of chancery. <ref name="NYT"/><ref name="HLM"/><ref name="HoC">{{cite book | url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/010822817 | title=History of the state of California and biographical record to Oakland and environs, also containing biographies of well-known citizens of the past and present | author=Guinn, J. M. | year=1907 | pages=467–8}}</ref><ref name="FA">{{cite web | url=http://cdn.calisphere.org/data/13030/pc/kt9c6040pc/files/kt9c6040pc.pdf | title=Finding aid of the John Whipple Dwinelle Papers C058835 | publisher=Society of California Pioneers | date=2011-11-29 | accessdate=2013-06-20 | author=Brown, Alexandria}}</ref>
In 1849, he sailed to San Francisco, California, and began a legal practice there. He served in a number of government offices, including two terms on the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors|San Francisco city council]], [[List of mayors of Oakland, California|Mayor]] of [[Oakland, California]], and member of the [[California State Assembly]] from [[Alameda County, California]].<ref name=HLM /><ref name=HoC />
Dwinelle represented the city of San Francisco in the so-called "[[pueblo]] case", ''[[Hart v. Burnett]]'', which secured San Francisco's claim to four square leagues of land due to the city's establishment as the pueblo of [[Yerba Buena, California|Yerba Buena]] under Mexican rule.<ref name="Bakken2000">{{cite book|author=Donald Louis Stelluto, Jr.|editor=Gordon Morris Bakken|title=Law in the Western United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zjHQWyttp6QC&pg=PA320|accessdate=25 June 2013|year=2000|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-3215-0|pages=317–25|chapter=The Fate of Pueblo Rights in Nineteenth-Century San Francisco}}</ref> Dwinelle's lengthy brief on these matters of land usage and history were published as ''The Colonial History of San Francisco'' (1863).<ref name="Tuthill1866">{{cite book|author=Franklin Tuthill|title=The History of California|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cR0VAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA107|accessdate=25 June 2013|year=1866|publisher=H. H. Bancroft|page=107}}</ref>
Dwinelle was also the lawyer in an important court case regarding [[school segregation]]. In ''[[Ward v. Flood]]'' (1874), he represented a black child who was refused enrollment at a San Francisco school. The [[Supreme Court of California]] ruled that black students could not be refused education under the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]], but that they could be denied entry into specific schools on the basis of race. This upheld the legal principle of "[[separate but equal]]" many years before the legal doctrine was adopted by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in ''[[Plessy v. Ferguson]]'' (1896). While this ruling did not desegregate California schools, it did guarantee the right of black students to an education.<ref name="Wollenberg1976">{{cite book|author=Charles Wollenberg|title=All Deliberate Speed: Segregation and Exclusion in California Schools, 1855-1975|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-nGoJQEdk_UC&pg=PA192&redir_esc=y#v=snippet&q=black%20children%20prohibiting&f=false|accessdate=20 June 2013|year=1976|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-03191-3|pages=22–24}}</ref>
As an Assemblyman, Dwinelle wrote and introduced the 1868 [[Organic Act]] establishing the [[University of California]].<ref name="Douglass2007">{{cite book|author=John Aubrey Douglass|title=The California Idea and American Higher Education: 1850 to the 1960 Master Plan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2UfpCfg095QC&pg=PA42|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=January 2007|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-5753-9|pages=42–3}}</ref> Dwinelle became one of the first [[Regents of the University of California]]. [[Dwinelle Hall]] at [[University of California, Berkeley]], the first campus opened as a result of Dwinelle's bill, is named for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spanish-portuguese.berkeley.edu/our-department/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510114658/http://spanish-portuguese.berkeley.edu/our-department/ |archivedate=2013-05-10 |df= }}</ref>
While trying to catch a ferry, Dwinelle fell from a pier in [[Port Costa, California]], and drowned.<ref name=NYT /> His body washed ashore three weeks later.<ref name=FA />
