{{short description|5th-century BC Roman consul}}
'''Lucius Aemilius Mamercus''' was a Roman statesman who served as [[roman consul|consul]] three times: in 484, 478 and 473 BC.<ref>[[Diodorus Siculus]], II.38, II.52, II.64</ref> <ref>[[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]], ''Roman Antiquities'', IX.37</ref> <ref name=Livy-2.42>[[Livy]], ''[[Ab urbe condita (book)|Ab urbe condita]]'', 2.42</ref>

In 484, as consul, Aemilius led the Roman forces in [[Roman-Aequian_wars#Ongoing_hostilities_from_485_BC|battle]] against the [[Volsci]] and [[Aequi]].  The Romans were successful, and the Roman cavalry slaughtered many in the rout which followed.<ref name=Livy-2.42/>

[[Livy]] says that during his first consulship, Aemilius (together with his colleague [[Caeso Fabius Vibulanus (consul)|Caeso Fabius Vibulanus]]) worked with the senate to oppose increases to the [[Tribune_of_the_Plebs#Powers_of_the_tribunes|powers of the tribunes]].<ref name=Livy-2.42/>

In 478 Aemilius led a Roman army successfully [[Roman–Etruscan_Wars#The_Fabian_war_with_Veii_in_483-476_BC|against the Etruscans]]. <ref>[[Livy|Titus Livius]], ''[[Ab Urbe Condita (book)|Ab Urbe Condita]]'', ii. 49.</ref>

