{{Taxobox | name = Serphitidae | image = | image_caption = | fossil_range = {{fossil_range|Mesozoic}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Evolution of the Insects|author=David Grimaldi, Michael S. Engel |editor=Cambridge University Press|year= 2005}}</ref> | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Arthropod]]a | classis = [[Insect]]a | ordo = [[Hymenoptera]] | subordo = [[Apocrita]] | superfamilia = | familia = '''Serphitidae''' | familia_authority = | subdivision_ranks = [[Subfamilies]] | subdivision = see [[#Subfamilies|below]]</small> }}
'''Serphitidae''' is a [[Family (biology)|family]] of [[fossil]] [[hymenoptera]]n insects.
== Taxonomy == This family was described in 1937 by the American entomologist [[Charles Thomas Brues]] to classify a fossil insect caught in an [[amber]] piece from Canada. The species was named ''[[Serphites paradoxus]]''. After that, more genera were described and included in this family, like ''[[Archaeromma]]'' and ''[[Distylopus]]'' by the Japanese entomologist [[Hiroshi Yoshimoto]] in 1975, from fossils also found in Canadian amber, and ''[[Aposerphites]]'', ''[[Microserphites]]'', ''[[Palaeomymar]]'' and new species of ''Serphites'' in 1979 by the Russian entomologist [[Mikhail Vasilievich Kozlov]] and [[Alexandr Rasnitsyn]], from [[Siberian]] amber .<ref>{{cite journal|author=George O. Poinar|title=Life in amber|editor=Stanford University Press|year=1992|pages=350|isbn=0804720010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J72FOr6AZOEC&lpg=PA216-IA4&dq=Serphitidae&pg=PA200#v=onepage&q=Serphitidae&f=false|access-date=13 August 2010}}</ref>
