{{India-reli-bio-stub}}

The term '''Toarcian turnover,''' alternatively the '''Toarcian extinction,''' the '''Pliensbachian-Toarcian extinction,''' or the '''Early Jurassic extinction,''' refers to the wave of extinctions that marked the end of the [[Pliensbachian]] stage and the start of the [[Toarcian]] stage of the [[Early Jurassic]] period, c. 183 million years ago.

The Toarcian turnover was most strongly manifested in aquatic lifeforms, notably in mollusk groups like [[ammonites]].<ref>Wignall, Paul B., and [[Anthony Hallam]]. ''Mass Extinctions and Their Aftermath.'' Oxford, Oxford University Press, 1997; pp. 164-5</ref><ref>[http://www.fossiel.net/locations/location.php?plaats=122 Location] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130629095614/http://www.fossiel.net/locations/location.php?plaats=122 |date=2013-06-29 }}</ref> Its reach was global in extent, as evidenced by research in European (peninsula of [[Peniche, Portugal]]<ref>[https://estudogeral.sib.uc.pt/bitstream/10316/20114/1/Rilo%20et%20al%202010.pdf Calcareous cliffs of Peniche peninsula (west coast of Portugal): geological heritage inventory  and characterization] - paper by A. R. Rilo, L. V. Duarte, and A. Tavares (in Portuguese, with abstract in Spanish and English)</ref><ref>[http://www.envegypt.com/EJEC/uploads/19.pdf The Evolution of the Coastline at Peniche and Berlengas Islands] – article by Teresa Azevedo, and Elisabete Nunes</ref>) and Japanese waters, the Andean basin, the floor of the former [[Tethys Sea]].<ref>MacLeod, Kenneth G., and Christian Koeberl. ''Catastrophic Events and Mass Extinctions: Impacts and Beyond.'' Boulder, CO, Geological Society of America, 2002; pp. 525-9.</ref> Evidence points to [[Hypoxia (environmental)|anoxic]] bottom waters as the probable cause of these marine extinctions, linked in turn to the massive volcanism of the [[Karoo-Ferrar]] eruptions in the relevant era.<ref>Marti, Joan, and Gerald Ernst. ''Volcanoes and the Environment.'' Cambridge, Cambridge University Press, 2005; p. 219.</ref> The Toarcian turnover was the seventh-largest [[mass extinction]] in Earth's history.<ref>[http://theconversation.com/volcanic-eruptions-once-caused-mass-extinctions-in-the-oceans-could-climate-change-do-the-same-99655 Volcanic eruptions once caused mass extinctions in the oceans – could climate change do the same?]</ref>

